00:12:23.990 --> 00:12:27.190
So, "Cinderella," of course, was
commissioned by CBS to be

00:12:27.190 --> 00:12:31.070
produced for TV back in
1957, broadcast live

00:12:31.070 --> 00:12:34.480
on March 31, 1957.

00:12:34.480 --> 00:12:37.810
Surrounding all of that, there's
a lot of reasoning, I

00:12:37.810 --> 00:12:41.170
guess, why it was brought back
or what brought it to Broadway

00:12:41.170 --> 00:12:43.370
in the first place.

00:12:43.370 --> 00:12:47.360
So Ted, you were kind of the
inspiration behind getting it

00:12:47.360 --> 00:12:49.732
from there to here.

00:12:49.732 --> 00:12:51.470
TED CHAPIN: Well, do we just--

00:12:51.470 --> 00:12:54.130
ALAN SEALES: No, we're
recording, so we need a mic.

00:12:54.130 --> 00:12:56.240
Yeah, let's get a
mic down here.

00:12:56.240 --> 00:12:58.190
TED CHAPIN: I mean, part
of the fun of my job--

00:12:58.190 --> 00:13:02.470
aside from hearing spontaneous
performances of songs from

00:13:02.470 --> 00:13:04.560
other Rodgers &amp; Hammerstein
shows, like "start at the very

00:13:04.560 --> 00:13:05.810
beginning"--

00:13:07.530 --> 00:13:09.960
the Rodgers &amp; Hammerstein
catalog is an extraordinary

00:13:09.960 --> 00:13:13.080
collection of musicals, as
you, I hope, all know.

00:13:13.080 --> 00:13:17.250
But there's always a creative
side that you never can tell

00:13:17.250 --> 00:13:19.740
where it's going to
happen and how.

00:13:19.740 --> 00:13:23.460
One of the lead producers of
"Cinderella" is Robyn Goodman,

00:13:23.460 --> 00:13:25.650
and she and I happened to be
on a trip that a Broadway

00:13:25.650 --> 00:13:29.080
producer named Manny Azenberg
does to Israel every year.

00:13:29.080 --> 00:13:32.160
And it's basically a trip for
people, wisenheimers who work

00:13:32.160 --> 00:13:35.340
in the theater to see this part
of the world, just to see

00:13:35.340 --> 00:13:36.080
this part of the world.

00:13:36.080 --> 00:13:38.480
And since my mother's family
came over on the "Mayflower,"

00:13:38.480 --> 00:13:40.480
I kept saying to Manny,
why are you asking

00:13:40.480 --> 00:13:41.290
me about this trip?

00:13:41.290 --> 00:13:42.690
It doesn't make any sense.

00:13:42.690 --> 00:13:44.450
So the only way to shut
him up was to go.

00:13:44.450 --> 00:13:46.960
So I went on a trip about five
years ago, and Robyn Goodman

00:13:46.960 --> 00:13:48.900
was on the trip, and
we just hit it off.

00:13:48.900 --> 00:13:50.890
And she said to me at one point,
gee, we're having such

00:13:50.890 --> 00:13:51.440
a good time together.

00:13:51.440 --> 00:13:53.260
Is there something
we could work on?

00:13:53.260 --> 00:13:56.390
And I said, you know, no one's
ever actually thought about or

00:13:56.390 --> 00:13:59.670
figured out how to take the
television version of

00:13:59.670 --> 00:14:02.490
"Cinderella" that Rodgers &amp;
Hammerstein wrote and adapt it

00:14:02.490 --> 00:14:05.030
to a Broadway show.

00:14:05.030 --> 00:14:06.390
So what about that?

00:14:06.390 --> 00:14:08.430
And she started to think, oh,
wouldn't it be great to make a

00:14:08.430 --> 00:14:12.480
modern Cinderella who stands up
for herself a little more?

00:14:12.480 --> 00:14:14.200
So basically, that's
where it started.

00:14:14.200 --> 00:14:17.730
And just over the years,
just one good idea

00:14:17.730 --> 00:14:19.080
after another happened.

00:14:19.080 --> 00:14:23.720
And so here we are with all of
these people doing incredible

00:14:23.720 --> 00:14:25.630
honor to this show.

00:14:25.630 --> 00:14:26.070
ALAN SEALES: Nice.

00:14:26.070 --> 00:14:32.330
So talk about, I guess, from
the audition side of things

00:14:32.330 --> 00:14:34.820
from the very beginning,
I guess--

00:14:34.820 --> 00:14:38.510
and I'm not making
the pun again.

00:14:38.510 --> 00:14:41.000
You start with a script, and
you go through revisions.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:46.680
And you need to find a
bookwriter, and you go through

00:14:46.680 --> 00:14:49.360
table readings and find
people to do so.

00:14:49.360 --> 00:14:51.760
And how did you find
these people?

00:14:51.760 --> 00:14:54.030
TED CHAPIN: Well, in the good
old days of Broadway, you

00:14:54.030 --> 00:14:56.800
would write a script and take
it out of town and do it in

00:14:56.800 --> 00:14:58.720
Boston or Philadelphia or
Washington or a couple of

00:14:58.720 --> 00:15:02.020
those places and listen to those
audiences and make the

00:15:02.020 --> 00:15:03.910
adjustments and then
come into town.

00:15:03.910 --> 00:15:07.500
That's pretty prohibitively
expensive these days.

00:15:07.500 --> 00:15:10.980
So the thing that Robyn and
her compadre Jill Furman,

00:15:10.980 --> 00:15:13.760
who's here, were very smart
about is starting with a very

00:15:13.760 --> 00:15:15.000
simple reading.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:16.670
There are all these
things available--

00:15:16.670 --> 00:15:18.310
readings, workshops--

00:15:18.310 --> 00:15:22.590
and they kind of used every
version of it to get the

00:15:22.590 --> 00:15:24.840
project to the next step.

00:15:24.840 --> 00:15:27.340
The very first reading, which
is very informal, and

00:15:27.340 --> 00:15:29.340
Laura was in it.

00:15:29.340 --> 00:15:31.795
And I remember my comment
about it.

00:15:31.795 --> 00:15:34.210
It was very funny and very
good, but they didn't, I

00:15:34.210 --> 00:15:36.510
think, pay enough attention
to the music.

00:15:36.510 --> 00:15:41.890
So I just said to Robyn, you
can't really do this without

00:15:41.890 --> 00:15:45.020
paying attention to both the
music that exists and whatever

00:15:45.020 --> 00:15:46.260
new music's going to
be put in there.

00:15:46.260 --> 00:15:49.640
Because if it's somebody like
Douglas Carter Beane, who has

00:15:49.640 --> 00:15:55.700
a very modern, edgy sense of
humor and sensibility, if

00:15:55.700 --> 00:15:58.530
that's going to match with the
kind of romance of what

00:15:58.530 --> 00:16:00.170
Rodgers &amp; Hammerstein
wrote, that's

00:16:00.170 --> 00:16:01.340
going to be very tricky.

00:16:01.340 --> 00:16:03.160
And I think that was the
biggest challenge.

00:16:03.160 --> 00:16:07.950
And I have to say that this team
really honed that right

00:16:07.950 --> 00:16:12.460
up to opening night, how to make
certain that the humor is

00:16:12.460 --> 00:16:16.090
right for the songs and the
songs come out of the story.

00:16:16.090 --> 00:16:19.120
And I have to say of all the
shows I've worked on in my

00:16:19.120 --> 00:16:21.580
days at R&amp;H, this was
among the more,

00:16:21.580 --> 00:16:24.690
first of all, joyous.

00:16:24.690 --> 00:16:25.830
Sure, there were the
ups and downs.

00:16:25.830 --> 00:16:26.660
There always are.

00:16:26.660 --> 00:16:29.560
But it was a really, really
joyous, positive experience.

00:16:29.560 --> 00:16:32.720
And just going backstage,
they're seeming to

00:16:32.720 --> 00:16:33.540
have a very good time.

00:16:33.540 --> 00:16:35.750
Either you're really, really
good actors, or you really are

00:16:35.750 --> 00:16:37.751
having a good time.

00:16:37.751 --> 00:16:40.760
ALAN SEALES: So Laura, you were
involved from the book

00:16:40.760 --> 00:16:42.430
reading at the beginning,
right?

00:16:42.430 --> 00:16:42.830
LAURA OSNES: Yes.

00:16:42.830 --> 00:16:45.280
That one he was talking about
was literally an afternoon

00:16:45.280 --> 00:16:48.810
where we got together and
literally read it out loud one

00:16:48.810 --> 00:16:49.575
time through.

00:16:49.575 --> 00:16:51.070
It was a very quick thing.

00:16:51.070 --> 00:16:53.750
And then it was about six
months of we didn't hear

00:16:53.750 --> 00:16:55.110
anything, or eight months
or whatever it was.

00:16:55.110 --> 00:16:58.170
And then our first reading with
all of these folks was

00:16:58.170 --> 00:17:01.540
January of 2012, so a
year and a half ago.

00:17:01.540 --> 00:17:04.730
And we did a workshop last
summer, a four-week-long

00:17:04.730 --> 00:17:07.650
workshop where we pretty much
staged the whole thing in a

00:17:07.650 --> 00:17:11.000
rehearsal studio with framework
sets and even

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:14.579
choreographed numbers and were
memorized and all of that.

00:17:14.579 --> 00:17:17.740
And then did another reading
last October of 2012, and then

00:17:17.740 --> 00:17:19.069
we started rehearsal
in December.

00:17:19.069 --> 00:17:23.450
So it's been really exciting to
see the changes in the show

00:17:23.450 --> 00:17:24.460
and how it's developed
over time.

00:17:24.460 --> 00:17:26.410
But I have to say, I think the
brunt of the changes came

00:17:26.410 --> 00:17:28.640
during previews on Broadway.

00:17:28.640 --> 00:17:31.160
Even though we had a year to
kind of prepare and shift

00:17:31.160 --> 00:17:34.470
things and make it better and
better, I feel like most of

00:17:34.470 --> 00:17:37.240
the changes happened once we
had a real audience and we

00:17:37.240 --> 00:17:39.560
were getting real feedback
from real people who were

00:17:39.560 --> 00:17:41.100
going to come see the show.

00:17:41.100 --> 00:17:43.540
ALAN SEALES: So for those who
don't know, what are previews?

00:17:43.540 --> 00:17:47.160
LAURA OSNES: Previews is the
month-long period before a

00:17:47.160 --> 00:17:49.400
show officially opens on
Broadway, and every Broadway

00:17:49.400 --> 00:17:52.240
show has as a season
of previews.

00:17:52.240 --> 00:17:54.900
So we had about 41
performances-- it's usually

00:17:54.900 --> 00:17:56.900
about a month long--

00:17:56.900 --> 00:18:00.560
where we're still rehearsing
during the day and performing

00:18:00.560 --> 00:18:01.140
every night.

00:18:01.140 --> 00:18:02.390
SANTINO FONTANA:
It's like beta.

00:18:05.260 --> 00:18:06.730
I know my audience.

00:18:06.730 --> 00:18:07.980
LAURA OSNES: There we go.

00:18:10.810 --> 00:18:14.410
So yeah, we're still making
changes every day.

00:18:14.410 --> 00:18:15.040
We're rehearsing.

00:18:15.040 --> 00:18:16.970
We're getting new script changes
based on how the

00:18:16.970 --> 00:18:18.830
previous night's audience
responded.

00:18:18.830 --> 00:18:22.140
So if jokes aren't getting
laughs three nights in a row,

00:18:22.140 --> 00:18:24.360
maybe that joke gets cut, or
maybe it gets changed.

00:18:24.360 --> 00:18:28.590
Or if a song isn't working,
maybe the song either gets cut

00:18:28.590 --> 00:18:31.230
or shifted or things
like that.

00:18:31.230 --> 00:18:33.840
So during previews, the show
is constantly changing.

00:18:33.840 --> 00:18:36.290
And then just a few days before
previews, we freeze the

00:18:36.290 --> 00:18:38.250
show for opening night.

00:18:38.250 --> 00:18:41.340
And from opening night on,
it's just the same show.

