I'm the voice of Excedrin.

00:50:47.840 --> 00:50:50.360
"Headaches are where
Excedrin excels."

00:50:50.360 --> 00:50:51.610
ALAN SEALES: That's you?

00:50:54.170 --> 00:50:55.150
SANTINO FONTANA: Google
it, please.

00:50:55.150 --> 00:50:56.140
Go buy some Excedrin.

00:50:56.140 --> 00:50:58.660
It'll help me.

00:50:58.660 --> 00:51:01.190
So that doesn't conflict, and
there are also things that

00:51:01.190 --> 00:51:03.690
work around your schedule
that don't conflict.

00:51:03.690 --> 00:51:07.820
And some things you audition
for, and they won't happen

00:51:07.820 --> 00:51:09.260
until next year.

00:51:09.260 --> 00:51:11.860
Or a writer wants to meet with
you because they have an idea

00:51:11.860 --> 00:51:15.150
for a part that they're
looking to do in 2015.

00:51:15.150 --> 00:51:17.170
So you can go out and do that.

00:51:17.170 --> 00:51:20.210
I mean, we all know the nature
of theater is it

00:51:20.210 --> 00:51:21.120
comes and it goes.

00:51:21.120 --> 00:51:23.560
So you're always looking
forward.

00:51:23.560 --> 00:51:24.890
MARLA MINDELLE: You're always
looking for the next job, even

00:51:24.890 --> 00:51:25.720
when you have a job.

00:51:25.720 --> 00:51:27.240
SANTINO FONTANA: Which doesn't
mean you're going to take the

00:51:27.240 --> 00:51:27.860
other one either.

00:51:27.860 --> 00:51:28.410
MARLA MINDELLE: Right.

00:51:28.410 --> 00:51:31.070
SANTINO FONTANA: But you know.

00:51:31.070 --> 00:51:32.080
HARRIET HARRIS: And we
have a contract.

00:51:32.080 --> 00:51:33.770
We know how long the
contract is.

00:51:33.770 --> 00:51:38.010
And we don't know if the show
extends beyond the contract if

00:51:38.010 --> 00:51:40.210
that will impact on
our lives or not.

00:51:40.210 --> 00:51:44.480
So you do have to keep an eye
towards the future, because

00:51:44.480 --> 00:51:47.210
you can't depend on
anything, really.

00:51:47.210 --> 00:51:50.400
Google's probably going
to be here tomorrow.

00:51:50.400 --> 00:51:51.070
ANN HARADA: Show business,
not so much.

00:51:51.070 --> 00:51:52.260
MARLA MINDELLE: "Cinderella"
will be too.

00:51:52.260 --> 00:51:54.650
HARRIET HARRIS: Sure, but--

00:51:54.650 --> 00:51:56.580
ALAN SEALES: I guess worst case,
knock on chair, that a

00:51:56.580 --> 00:51:59.270
show unexpectedly gets canceled,
that ends your

00:51:59.270 --> 00:52:01.720
contract early, and you
have no control.

00:52:01.720 --> 00:52:02.410
ANN HARADA: Correct.

00:52:02.410 --> 00:52:04.820
ALAN SEALES: So you've got to
be doing the next thing.

00:52:04.820 --> 00:52:06.710
MARLA MINDELLE: We've
been very fortunate.

00:52:06.710 --> 00:52:07.730
Who doesn't love Cinderella?

00:52:07.730 --> 00:52:08.770
Who doesn't want to
come see the show?

00:52:08.770 --> 00:52:12.100
And every child wants their
family to take it, so our

00:52:12.100 --> 00:52:13.590
ticket sales have been doing--

00:52:13.590 --> 00:52:13.990
SANTINO FONTANA: Very well.

00:52:13.990 --> 00:52:14.640
MARLA MINDELLE: Yeah.

00:52:14.640 --> 00:52:16.040
Very, very well,
which is great.

00:52:16.040 --> 00:52:19.690
Which means that we have
a job for at least--

00:52:19.690 --> 00:52:20.830
well, we have what?

00:52:20.830 --> 00:52:21.380
A year contract?

00:52:21.380 --> 00:52:21.980
ANN HARADA: Mm hmm.

00:52:21.980 --> 00:52:23.680
MARLA MINDELLE: So we started
in January, which means that

00:52:23.680 --> 00:52:25.270
this January, our contract
will be up.

00:52:25.270 --> 00:52:29.330
And we can choose to re-sign
or we can choose to end the

00:52:29.330 --> 00:52:30.270
contract and look for
the next thing.

00:52:30.270 --> 00:52:30.905
ANN HARADA: Or they
could get fire us.

00:52:30.905 --> 00:52:31.720
SANTINO FONTANA: Yeah.

00:52:31.720 --> 00:52:33.520
MARLA MINDELLE: Or
we can get fired.

00:52:33.520 --> 00:52:34.343
I don't think that's
going happen.

00:52:34.343 --> 00:52:35.190
I hope not.

00:52:35.190 --> 00:52:37.230
ALAN SEALES: Over here?

00:52:37.230 --> 00:52:38.432
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:52:38.432 --> 00:52:40.880
OK, my question is
kind of cliche.

00:52:40.880 --> 00:52:44.370
But if you could give one piece
of advice to people who

00:52:44.370 --> 00:52:48.170
want to do this for a living,
what would it be?

00:52:48.170 --> 00:52:48.800
ALAN SEALES: She's a visitor.

00:52:48.800 --> 00:52:49.120
She's not a Googler.

00:52:49.120 --> 00:52:50.370
I looked.

00:52:52.310 --> 00:52:54.020
SANTINO FONTANA: I
was gonna say.

00:52:54.020 --> 00:52:54.960
MARLA MINDELLE: Going
on secret job

00:52:54.960 --> 00:52:56.210
interviews/auditions?

00:52:59.450 --> 00:53:00.963
Oh, gosh, we all have
such different,

00:53:00.963 --> 00:53:04.350
different pieces of advice.

00:53:04.350 --> 00:53:09.360
I always talk about going
to a good college.

00:53:09.360 --> 00:53:11.778
But if you haven't gone to
a good college, oof.

00:53:14.300 --> 00:53:15.700
Well, you know what I mean.

00:53:15.700 --> 00:53:16.695
Like if you went for
accounting--

00:53:16.695 --> 00:53:17.600
SANTINO FONTANA: And
just it's over.

00:53:17.600 --> 00:53:20.350
Just kill the dream.

00:53:20.350 --> 00:53:21.930
ALAN SEALES: Let me see if
I can lead you guys here.

00:53:21.930 --> 00:53:23.980
In my experience--

00:53:23.980 --> 00:53:26.100
I used to perform to as
well, and that's why I

00:53:26.100 --> 00:53:27.530
breathe them in--

00:53:27.530 --> 00:53:29.900
the people I see succeed over
those who don't are those who

00:53:29.900 --> 00:53:32.170
know how to market themselves.

00:53:32.170 --> 00:53:33.360
MARLA MINDELLE: Interesting.

00:53:33.360 --> 00:53:35.260
ANN HARADA: I don't see
it that way at all.

00:53:35.260 --> 00:53:36.570
SANTINO FONTANA: I have
to say, I am a

00:53:36.570 --> 00:53:37.860
terrible marketer of myself.

00:53:37.860 --> 00:53:38.750
ANN HARADA: He sucks.

00:53:38.750 --> 00:53:39.560
SANTINO FONTANA: I'm terrible.

00:53:39.560 --> 00:53:41.350
I'd rather be like,
I'm two steps away

00:53:41.350 --> 00:53:42.565
from a homeless person.

00:53:42.565 --> 00:53:44.390
Just put me in a corner
with some food.

00:53:44.390 --> 00:53:45.510
Just leave me alone.

00:53:45.510 --> 00:53:48.740
I'm a terrible marketer
of myself.

00:53:48.740 --> 00:53:50.620
I understand your commenting
that you

00:53:50.620 --> 00:53:51.660
feel like it's cliche.

00:53:51.660 --> 00:53:54.360
The answer is somewhat
cliche, sadly.

00:53:54.360 --> 00:53:57.660
First of all, you've just got
to do it, and the operative

00:53:57.660 --> 00:54:00.160
word there is "do." So if you
want to be an actor, you've

00:54:00.160 --> 00:54:01.180
got to be acting.

00:54:01.180 --> 00:54:03.120
And that doesn't mean
necessarily on Broadway.

00:54:03.120 --> 00:54:05.570
That means in a class.

00:54:05.570 --> 00:54:09.460
Because identifying what you
want to do is, first of all,

00:54:09.460 --> 00:54:11.460
honing in on what that really
specifically means.

00:54:11.460 --> 00:54:14.140
I was talking to a student who
asked, I want to do what

00:54:14.140 --> 00:54:14.780
you're doing.

00:54:14.780 --> 00:54:15.640
How do I do that?

00:54:15.640 --> 00:54:17.720
And I was like, well, what
do you want to do?

00:54:17.720 --> 00:54:20.240
I want to be an actor.

00:54:20.240 --> 00:54:22.350
So you want to tell stories
as characters?

00:54:22.350 --> 00:54:23.020
Yes.

00:54:23.020 --> 00:54:25.330
What kind of stories?

00:54:25.330 --> 00:54:26.090
Well, musicals.

00:54:26.090 --> 00:54:28.430
OK, well, that's very different
than if you want to

00:54:28.430 --> 00:54:30.600
go be in movies or television
or if you want to be in

00:54:30.600 --> 00:54:31.090
straight plays.

00:54:31.090 --> 00:54:32.910
If you want to do classical
theater, you need another

00:54:32.910 --> 00:54:33.530
understanding.

00:54:33.530 --> 00:54:36.540
You need to be able
to do verse.

00:54:36.540 --> 00:54:39.970
There's so many skills that
are potentially required.

00:54:39.970 --> 00:54:42.520
First, what is most important is
to identify what skills do

00:54:42.520 --> 00:54:44.110
you need to go after.

00:54:44.110 --> 00:54:45.950
Because what do you
really want to do?

00:54:45.950 --> 00:54:47.520
What speaks to you?

00:54:47.520 --> 00:54:51.160
And that's easy, because you
can go out and find that.

00:54:51.160 --> 00:54:52.290
And it's a process.

00:54:52.290 --> 00:54:55.290
My biggest advice really would
be to take any sense of

00:54:55.290 --> 00:54:57.670
pressure off of your
shoulders.

00:54:57.670 --> 00:55:01.280
Morgan Freeman was 40 when
he made his first movie.

00:55:01.280 --> 00:55:04.570
James Gandolfini, who just
passed, he didn't come to

00:55:04.570 --> 00:55:06.640
acting until after college.

00:55:06.640 --> 00:55:08.170
There's no rush.

00:55:08.170 --> 00:55:08.950
There's no rush.

00:55:08.950 --> 00:55:11.680
There's 8 million ways to
skin that cat, but you

00:55:11.680 --> 00:55:14.280
have to go after it.

00:55:14.280 --> 00:55:17.060
And you can do that while you're
doing other things.

00:55:17.060 --> 00:55:20.920
ALAN SEALES: If you guys could
do any role from any time

00:55:20.920 --> 00:55:23.340
ever, what would you do?

00:55:23.340 --> 00:55:24.150
MARLA MINDELLE: You
mean Broadway?

00:55:24.150 --> 00:55:26.000
ALAN SEALES: Anything, Well,
yeah, let's stick to Broadway.

00:55:26.000 --> 00:55:27.960
Let's focus this.

00:55:27.960 --> 00:55:28.870
We'll say Broadway.

00:55:28.870 --> 00:55:30.822
MARLA MINDELLE: These are such
hard-hitting questions.

00:55:33.750 --> 00:55:37.040
ALAN SEALES: Let's get to the
meat of the situation, Marla.

00:55:37.040 --> 00:55:38.140
MARLA MINDELLE: Oh, gosh.

00:55:38.140 --> 00:55:38.670
Evita.

00:55:38.670 --> 00:55:41.270
I've always wanted
to be Elphaba--

00:55:41.270 --> 00:55:43.250
just for one week though,
because it seems too hard to

00:55:43.250 --> 00:55:45.330
do for longer than a week.

00:55:45.330 --> 00:55:46.280
ALAN SEALES: Elphaba
from "Wicked."

00:55:46.280 --> 00:55:47.440
MARLA MINDELLE: From "Wicked,"
yes, yes, yes.

00:55:47.440 --> 00:55:51.990
From the Broadway musical
"Wicked." I've wanted to play

00:55:51.990 --> 00:55:55.930
Ann Harada in "Smash"
at one point.

00:55:55.930 --> 00:55:57.240
ALAN SEALES: That want one of
my questions, if you could

00:55:57.240 --> 00:55:58.920
trade with somebody to do
one of their roles.

00:55:58.920 --> 00:55:59.890
MARLA MINDELLE: Oh, definitely
Ann Harada.

00:55:59.890 --> 00:56:01.140
Definitely.

00:56:03.940 --> 00:56:06.740
She's so disgusted.

00:56:06.740 --> 00:56:09.180
ANN HARADA: I don't know.

00:56:09.180 --> 00:56:10.880
I feel like there's some great
roles out there that I don't

00:56:10.880 --> 00:56:15.000
think I personally have the
chops to play, so I wouldn't

00:56:15.000 --> 00:56:17.730
pick those.

00:56:17.730 --> 00:56:20.090
I'd like to play Dolly in
"Hello, Dolly!" I'd like to

00:56:20.090 --> 00:56:21.500
play Mrs. Lovett.

00:56:21.500 --> 00:56:22.750
Harriet has played
Mrs. Lovett.

00:56:22.750 --> 00:56:24.780
I'm very jealous of her.

00:56:24.780 --> 00:56:27.740
I think every musical theater
actress thinks about playing

00:56:27.740 --> 00:56:32.600
Rose in "Gypsy," at least
people of the character

00:56:32.600 --> 00:56:34.860
persuasion do.

00:56:34.860 --> 00:56:35.350
Things like that.

00:56:35.350 --> 00:56:37.540
Those are, to me, mountains
that would be

00:56:37.540 --> 00:56:38.790
great to climb someday.

00:56:41.320 --> 00:56:45.230
But I want to go back to the
previous question about

00:56:45.230 --> 00:56:47.460
marketing yourself.

00:56:47.460 --> 00:56:48.440
It doesn't matter.

00:56:48.440 --> 00:56:50.830
You don't need that.

00:56:50.830 --> 00:56:55.550
You need to get out there, do
stuff with people, do stuff

00:56:55.550 --> 00:56:57.460
with your friends.

00:56:57.460 --> 00:56:58.800
I sort of feel like
that's the way.

00:56:58.800 --> 00:57:00.830
Because only once you start
working with people, they'll

00:57:00.830 --> 00:57:02.040
think of you for
the next thing.

00:57:02.040 --> 00:57:03.290
And it all sort of snowballs.

00:57:06.005 --> 00:57:07.570
You don't all have to play
in the same field.

00:57:07.570 --> 00:57:09.070
I don't need to be
a movie star.

00:57:09.070 --> 00:57:10.980
I don't need to be a TV star.

00:57:10.980 --> 00:57:13.250
I like acting for
acting's sake.

00:57:13.250 --> 00:57:16.450
I'm happy to be in a little box
in the East Village, and

00:57:16.450 --> 00:57:18.310
I'm happy on Broadway.

00:57:18.310 --> 00:57:19.560
Do you know what I mean?

00:57:19.560 --> 00:57:21.410
So to me, it's all the same.

00:57:21.410 --> 00:57:22.760
You're performing, and
you're trying to

00:57:22.760 --> 00:57:25.820
bring truth to something.

00:57:25.820 --> 00:57:29.480
HARRIET HARRIS: And I think
one of the things that

00:57:29.480 --> 00:57:32.780
distinguishes actors is why
they want to be an actor.

00:57:32.780 --> 00:57:35.420
Some people just think, because
I want to perform.

00:57:35.420 --> 00:57:36.660
I want to entertain.

00:57:36.660 --> 00:57:40.390
Or some people say, because I
love that sensation of all

00:57:40.390 --> 00:57:41.010
that attention.

00:57:41.010 --> 00:57:43.080
I like all eyes on the
high board and

00:57:43.080 --> 00:57:44.530
being on the high board.

00:57:44.530 --> 00:57:47.050
I don't mean that.

00:57:47.050 --> 00:57:48.300
I like to tell a story.

00:57:48.300 --> 00:57:49.510
I like to relate to people.

00:57:49.510 --> 00:57:51.880
I'm a little usually of scared
people, unless it's a

00:57:51.880 --> 00:57:53.410
situation like this,
where you're really

00:57:53.410 --> 00:57:55.950
far away from me.

00:57:55.950 --> 00:58:01.290
But it's a great way for me to
communicate ideas that are

00:58:01.290 --> 00:58:03.950
usually formulated
in a much more

00:58:03.950 --> 00:58:06.190
succinct way than I think.

00:58:06.190 --> 00:58:13.800
So it's a chance to engage
and educate and say

00:58:13.800 --> 00:58:15.880
this exists in life.

00:58:15.880 --> 00:58:18.900
And it's a safe way for you to
look at it, and it's a safe

00:58:18.900 --> 00:58:21.080
way for us to talk about it.

00:58:21.080 --> 00:58:22.600
And it's challenging
at the same time.

00:58:22.600 --> 00:58:26.250
So people are actors for all
sorts of different reasons.

00:58:26.250 --> 00:58:32.480
But you really have to, I think,
devote yourself to what

00:58:32.480 --> 00:58:34.130
you expect to get out of it.

00:58:34.130 --> 00:58:37.890
And I think that what Ann was
talking about it being just as

00:58:37.890 --> 00:58:39.260
credible anyplace.

00:58:39.260 --> 00:58:40.210
It's true.

00:58:40.210 --> 00:58:42.580
It doesn't matter.

00:58:42.580 --> 00:58:45.740
Actors generally feel successful
if they're acting.

00:58:45.740 --> 00:58:48.290
And you don't have to make a lot
of money unless your goal

00:58:48.290 --> 00:58:50.910
is to make money, and then you
really shouldn't be an actor.

00:58:50.910 --> 00:58:54.360
You should really be something
else if that's what you need.

00:58:54.360 --> 00:58:56.800
And really, if you really need a
lot of attention, you should

00:58:56.800 --> 00:58:58.740
be something else.

00:58:58.740 --> 00:59:03.380
And I'm not saying you, but
I mean, one should.

00:59:03.380 --> 00:59:07.140
The more you can define what you
expect for it to bring you

00:59:07.140 --> 00:59:11.660
or want to contribute to it
more, like Santino was talking

00:59:11.660 --> 00:59:14.380
about, the more you can define
that, the happier you probably

00:59:14.380 --> 00:59:17.090
will be and the happier
you are as an actor.

00:59:17.090 --> 00:59:21.072
You'll have more longevity,
I think.

00:59:21.072 --> 00:59:21.510
ALAN SEALES: Nice.

00:59:21.510 --> 00:59:24.710
Yes, next question.

00:59:24.710 --> 00:59:25.190
AUDIENCE: Hi, guys.

00:59:25.190 --> 00:59:27.810
I saw the play and I loved it,
so it's really fun to see you

00:59:27.810 --> 00:59:29.170
all in person.

00:59:29.170 --> 00:59:33.180
My question is if you have any
embarrassing onstage moments

00:59:33.180 --> 00:59:36.205
from either "Cinderella" or a
previous role that you'd want

00:59:36.205 --> 00:59:38.192
to share with us.

00:59:38.192 --> 00:59:41.490
MARLA MINDELLE: It's an
ongoing embarrassment.

00:59:41.490 --> 00:59:42.240
SANTINO FONTANA:
Tell the story.

00:59:42.240 --> 00:59:43.250
Tell the story.

00:59:43.250 --> 00:59:43.640
Yesterday.

00:59:43.640 --> 00:59:44.410
HARRIET HARRIS: Yesterday?

00:59:44.410 --> 00:59:45.690
SANTINO FONTANA: Yeah.

00:59:45.690 --> 00:59:46.350
HARRIET HARRIS: All right.

00:59:46.350 --> 00:59:50.880
We're approaching
our 200th show.

00:59:50.880 --> 00:59:54.390
I really love the show, and I
really love everybody in it.

00:59:54.390 --> 00:59:57.270
And possibly I'm sleep deprived,
I don't know.

00:59:57.270 --> 01:00:01.750
But I got to a certain point
in the afternoon and, of

01:00:01.750 --> 01:00:04.450
course, I just couldn't think
of the next word.

01:00:04.450 --> 01:00:05.650
And this does happen.

01:00:05.650 --> 01:00:08.935
It starts happening in your
40s, and it continues.

01:00:11.540 --> 01:00:14.090
So I say, "Oh, isn't it
wonderful how the needy just

01:00:14.090 --> 01:00:19.120
keep on going?" So I had said,
"Isn't it wonderful how the

01:00:19.120 --> 01:00:26.000
needy just keep on moving?"

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:28.270
So I thought, OK,
that was bad.

01:00:28.270 --> 01:00:29.520
And then I look over,
and Marla's like--

01:00:32.870 --> 01:00:34.340
Because Marla's so young,
she doesn't

01:00:34.340 --> 01:00:35.420
make mistakes on stage.

01:00:35.420 --> 01:00:36.600
MARLA MINDELLE: Not
true, not true.

01:00:36.600 --> 01:00:38.520
HARRIET HARRIS: And Ann is
like, oh, how bad is this

01:00:38.520 --> 01:00:39.960
going to get?

01:00:39.960 --> 01:00:40.690
This could get really bad.

01:00:40.690 --> 01:00:42.210
Harriet's got more
lines to go.

01:00:42.210 --> 01:00:45.670
So anyway, in the evening I
thought, I am tired, but I'm

01:00:45.670 --> 01:00:47.070
not going to make that
mistake again.

01:00:47.070 --> 01:00:49.810
So I got to, "Isn't it wonderful
how the needy just

01:00:49.810 --> 01:00:55.340
keep on--" I couldn't remember
"going." I couldn't remember

01:00:55.340 --> 01:01:00.290
"moving." I just, what is
something like that?

01:01:03.490 --> 01:01:06.320
So it started guess to sound
like a Katharine Hepburn

01:01:06.320 --> 01:01:06.960
impersonation.

01:01:06.960 --> 01:01:12.385
"Isn't it wonderful how the
needy just keep on--"

01:01:12.385 --> 01:01:14.810
And I thought, I'm going to say
"keep on trucking." I know

01:01:14.810 --> 01:01:17.210
it's going to come out, and
it's going be like some R.

01:01:17.210 --> 01:01:19.990
Crumb cartoon where this
guy is going across.

01:01:19.990 --> 01:01:20.920
But I didn't.

01:01:20.920 --> 01:01:25.290
And finally, I came up with
"moving" again, and both Ann

01:01:25.290 --> 01:01:26.830
and Marla sort of looked--

01:01:26.830 --> 01:01:27.350
MARLA MINDELLE: I always
look at her.

01:01:27.350 --> 01:01:29.700
I always smile at her
afterwards, because I want to

01:01:29.700 --> 01:01:32.790
see her break or see if she'll
giggle or something.

01:01:32.790 --> 01:01:35.660
So the next line she said
completely up to the ceiling,

01:01:35.660 --> 01:01:39.540
because she didn't want to
make eye contact with us,

01:01:39.540 --> 01:01:42.170
which then made me
laugh even more.

01:01:42.170 --> 01:01:44.450
HARRIET HARRIS: And it just got
worse and worse, and I was

01:01:44.450 --> 01:01:46.840
so overwhelmed about having
made that mistake.

01:01:46.840 --> 01:01:48.040
And then I came back in.

01:01:48.040 --> 01:01:50.160
In the next scene, I thought,
oh, completely recovered.

01:01:50.160 --> 01:01:50.880
It's fine, fine.

01:01:50.880 --> 01:01:54.520
A few scenes later, well, I run
in with this invitation.

01:01:54.520 --> 01:01:56.170
And now the prince's is
not giving a ball,

01:01:56.170 --> 01:01:57.430
he's giving a banquet.

01:01:57.430 --> 01:01:59.950
And I run in, and I have
to shut the door.

01:01:59.950 --> 01:02:02.635
And I ran, and I went, you
didn't shut the door.

01:02:02.635 --> 01:02:04.495
You gotta go back and
shut the door.

01:02:04.495 --> 01:02:06.820
So I go back and
shut the door.

01:02:06.820 --> 01:02:10.770
And this is a line that I do all
on one breath, because it

01:02:10.770 --> 01:02:13.560
just has to be that way for
there to be a response.

01:02:13.560 --> 01:02:18.130
And so I go back,
and I'm running.

01:02:18.130 --> 01:02:20.350
And the costume's like
40 pounds, so I'm

01:02:20.350 --> 01:02:21.840
running, going back.

01:02:21.840 --> 01:02:22.940
I'm running, shutting
the door.

01:02:22.940 --> 01:02:25.950
And then I lose the invitation,
and the invitation

01:02:25.950 --> 01:02:26.980
flutters out of my hand.

01:02:26.980 --> 01:02:29.515
And I go over, and I'm so
awkward, because I've got this

01:02:29.515 --> 01:02:30.560
huge hoop skirt on.

01:02:30.560 --> 01:02:34.510
So I'm trying to get down, and
I can't get the invitation.

01:02:34.510 --> 01:02:38.070
And then I thought I had it, and
I came up, and it's empty.

01:02:38.070 --> 01:02:41.060
So I had to reach down again,
get the invitation.

01:02:41.060 --> 01:02:43.380
MARLA MINDELLE: And I'm on stage
with her once again,

01:02:43.380 --> 01:02:45.288
watching this entire thing.

01:02:45.288 --> 01:02:48.410
HARRIET HARRIS: It was like my
life is flashing before me.

01:02:48.410 --> 01:02:50.050
MARLA MINDELLE: But you
would never notice it.

01:02:50.050 --> 01:02:52.650
And that's what I love about
it, is that it's so subtle.

01:02:52.650 --> 01:02:54.370
And the only people that can
tell what's happening--

01:02:54.370 --> 01:02:54.900
well, maybe not.

01:02:54.900 --> 01:02:57.584
Maybe not just trying to get the
invitation off the floor.

01:02:57.584 --> 01:02:59.510
HARRIET HARRIS: It was
a little awkward.

01:02:59.510 --> 01:03:00.390
MARLA MINDELLE: But
the prior scene.

01:03:00.390 --> 01:03:05.200
Like the "keep on moving."
No one would

01:03:05.200 --> 01:03:06.260
tell, but we can tell.

01:03:06.260 --> 01:03:10.920
And it's just a flicker of the
eye where you identify, oh,

01:03:10.920 --> 01:03:13.485
that was a little
screw up there.

01:03:13.485 --> 01:03:14.700
I caught you.

01:03:14.700 --> 01:03:16.680
HARRIET HARRIS: Vicky has
gotten stuck in midair a

01:03:16.680 --> 01:03:17.350
couple of times.

01:03:17.350 --> 01:03:19.740
MARLA MINDELLE: Our
set has stopped.

01:03:19.740 --> 01:03:20.290
HARRIET HARRIS: These
things are

01:03:20.290 --> 01:03:21.510
accidents, or they're mistakes.

01:03:21.510 --> 01:03:21.910
ALAN SEALES: The godmother,
Fairy Godmother.

01:03:21.910 --> 01:03:22.090
MARLA MINDELLE: Yeah.

01:03:22.090 --> 01:03:24.380
HARRIET HARRIS: But nothing
horrible really happens other

01:03:24.380 --> 01:03:27.100
than humiliation.

01:03:27.100 --> 01:03:27.735
SANTINO FONTANA: I fell.

01:03:27.735 --> 01:03:29.840
I came in all my armor.

01:03:29.840 --> 01:03:31.720
The very first scene, I come
in in all that armor.

01:03:31.720 --> 01:03:35.210
And I step up on a tree log, and
I pose, and there's a big

01:03:35.210 --> 01:03:37.210
light that hits me,
and trumpets play.

01:03:37.210 --> 01:03:37.790
It was like, yay!

01:03:37.790 --> 01:03:41.020
And I fell.

01:03:41.020 --> 01:03:43.650
That happened yesterday, where
I was like, I'm now--

01:03:43.650 --> 01:03:44.550
nope.

01:03:44.550 --> 01:03:47.646
I just went down and
went back up again.

01:03:47.646 --> 01:03:51.430
Oh, it's terrible, terrible.

01:03:51.430 --> 01:03:52.040
ALAN SEALES: Next question.

01:03:52.040 --> 01:03:54.960
Yeah, I think we're running
pretty close on time here.

01:03:54.960 --> 01:03:56.870
AUDIENCE: Hi, two-part
question.

01:03:56.870 --> 01:03:59.830
One is, what is each of your
favorite Broadway shows?

01:03:59.830 --> 01:04:01.480
It doesn't have to be
one you've been in.

01:04:01.480 --> 01:04:03.290
It could be one that
you've seen.

01:04:03.290 --> 01:04:06.240
And then also, when you are
going and you're in the

01:04:06.240 --> 01:04:10.000
audience seeing a show, you
probably experience it

01:04:10.000 --> 01:04:13.270
differently than we would.

01:04:13.270 --> 01:04:15.830
Are you thinking about what
they're doing backstage?

01:04:15.830 --> 01:04:16.780
What sort of goes through
your mind?

01:04:16.780 --> 01:04:17.120
MARLA MINDELLE: I do.

01:04:17.120 --> 01:04:17.900
I think about that.

01:04:17.900 --> 01:04:20.040
And also, it's a lot like high
school, because it's such a

01:04:20.040 --> 01:04:21.070
small world.

01:04:21.070 --> 01:04:23.890
I feel a lot of joy, because
we see all of

01:04:23.890 --> 01:04:25.160
our friends on stage.

01:04:25.160 --> 01:04:29.470
It's like we know somebody
in almost every show.

01:04:29.470 --> 01:04:32.040
So yeah, it's a fun experience
for me, because I get to see

01:04:32.040 --> 01:04:36.770
the people that I love
doing their thing.

01:04:36.770 --> 01:04:38.030
That's me.

01:04:38.030 --> 01:04:39.340
ALAN SEALES: What's your
favorite show?

01:04:39.340 --> 01:04:40.810
MARLA MINDELLE: Oh, "Ghost
the Musical," which

01:04:40.810 --> 01:04:41.640
only ran for like--

01:04:41.640 --> 01:04:42.090
[APPLAUSE]

01:04:42.090 --> 01:04:42.670
MARLA MINDELLE: Really?

01:04:42.670 --> 01:04:42.930
AUDIENCE: Yes!

01:04:42.930 --> 01:04:43.910
MARLA MINDELLE: Oh my god.

01:04:43.910 --> 01:04:44.870
Everyone hated it.

01:04:44.870 --> 01:04:45.570
I loved it.

01:04:45.570 --> 01:04:46.280
I saw it four times.

01:04:46.280 --> 01:04:48.760
I took him to see it.

01:04:48.760 --> 01:04:49.980
ALAN SEALES: It was
an experience.

01:04:49.980 --> 01:04:52.100
MARLA MINDELLE: It was an
experience, to say the least.

01:04:52.100 --> 01:04:52.740
I loved it.

01:04:52.740 --> 01:04:56.060
But also I love, of course,
"Gypsy": and "Sunday in the

01:04:56.060 --> 01:05:02.020
Park with George." I'm a purist
at heart as well, even

01:05:02.020 --> 01:05:04.890
though I loved "Ghost." But
I like a lot of the

01:05:04.890 --> 01:05:06.340
old-fashioned ones as well.

01:05:06.340 --> 01:05:08.220
That's what I was raised on.

01:05:08.220 --> 01:05:09.770
So all of them?

01:05:09.770 --> 01:05:12.420
I don't know.

01:05:12.420 --> 01:05:15.050
HARRIET HARRIS: I guess my
favorite show I ever saw--

01:05:15.050 --> 01:05:18.590
and I don't think that's really
true anymore, but it

01:05:18.590 --> 01:05:23.430
may as well be true, because
it's the one that hit me most

01:05:23.430 --> 01:05:24.520
viscerally--

01:05:24.520 --> 01:05:27.490
was the "Sweeney Todd" that
Angela Lansbury and I saw Len

01:05:27.490 --> 01:05:29.000
Cariou too do it.

01:05:29.000 --> 01:05:32.340
And it was wonderful.

01:05:32.340 --> 01:05:34.940
I loved that show.

01:05:34.940 --> 01:05:39.820
But sometimes I go see things
now, and the things that I'm

01:05:39.820 --> 01:05:44.020
most thrilled by is not what
the audience adores.

01:05:44.020 --> 01:05:47.130
Because sometimes I just think
the audience expects so much

01:05:47.130 --> 01:05:53.190
now, and they don't always
recognize that this incredible

01:05:53.190 --> 01:05:54.760
little thing just happened.

01:05:54.760 --> 01:05:56.880
And people don't know how
hard that incredible

01:05:56.880 --> 01:05:58.120
little thing is.

01:05:58.120 --> 01:06:00.970
And sometimes it's just two
actors talking to each other

01:06:00.970 --> 01:06:06.400
for a few moments, and the
whole stage just seems to

01:06:06.400 --> 01:06:10.250
vibrate and shimmer, because
they're so incredibly good.

01:06:10.250 --> 01:06:13.570
And you just think, I hope that
everybody's getting that.

01:06:13.570 --> 01:06:15.710
But it's not the thing
that people leap

01:06:15.710 --> 01:06:17.650
up and go wow about.

01:06:17.650 --> 01:06:21.810
And I kind of think, well, why
aren't we leaping up and going

01:06:21.810 --> 01:06:23.520
wow about that stuff?

01:06:23.520 --> 01:06:28.930
That to me is real artistry
and so beautiful.

01:06:28.930 --> 01:06:31.790
So that's what I get excited
about most of the time, those

01:06:31.790 --> 01:06:32.810
sort of times.

01:06:32.810 --> 01:06:35.290
ANN HARADA: My favorite show
was also that production of

01:06:35.290 --> 01:06:39.820
"Sweeney Todd" that I saw
the day it won the Tony.

01:06:39.820 --> 01:06:47.520
And "Nicholas Nickleby," the
Royal Shakespeare Company's

01:06:47.520 --> 01:06:49.950
four-hour version of "Nicholas
Nickleby."

01:06:49.950 --> 01:06:50.800
Four and a half hours.

01:06:50.800 --> 01:06:52.050
It was awesome.

01:06:56.070 --> 01:06:56.720
I feel the same way.

01:06:56.720 --> 01:07:01.260
I feel like we go to see shows,
and we are judging them

01:07:01.260 --> 01:07:03.900
from a totally different
perspective almost.

01:07:03.900 --> 01:07:06.770
And so for me, when I see
a particularly amazing

01:07:06.770 --> 01:07:12.800
performance or a scene that
makes my heart go, oh, that

01:07:12.800 --> 01:07:16.970
was perfect, that's what sort
of sticks in my head, as

01:07:16.970 --> 01:07:20.280
opposed to that was
a really cool set.

01:07:20.280 --> 01:07:22.680
I never think that.

01:07:22.680 --> 01:07:24.700
SANTINO FONTANA: Funnily enough,
"Sweeney Todd" is also

01:07:24.700 --> 01:07:26.000
my favorite show.

01:07:26.000 --> 01:07:29.080
And I saw the videotape of the
tour of Angela Lansbury with

01:07:29.080 --> 01:07:30.700
George Hearn back when
I was a kid.

01:07:30.700 --> 01:07:32.480
Someone from my high school
showed it to me, and I thought

01:07:32.480 --> 01:07:34.910
it was incredible.

01:07:34.910 --> 01:07:35.470
So that.

01:07:35.470 --> 01:07:37.730
And I think, yeah, we're
more critical.

01:07:37.730 --> 01:07:40.770
But I think probably the biggest
difference is it's

01:07:40.770 --> 01:07:42.610
just much more casual.

01:07:42.610 --> 01:07:44.170
My parents come, and they're
like, oh, we've

01:07:44.170 --> 01:07:44.950
got to go get dressed.

01:07:44.950 --> 01:07:46.230
I'm like, no you don't.

01:07:46.230 --> 01:07:48.310
I'll go wearing whatever.

01:07:48.310 --> 01:07:50.690
It's just much more like, and
now we're going to see a play.

01:07:50.690 --> 01:07:51.920
We're going to go.

01:07:51.920 --> 01:07:54.350
I think that's probably the
biggest difference.

01:07:54.350 --> 01:07:57.230
And to be honest, especially
when you're in a long-running

01:07:57.230 --> 01:07:59.820
show like this, the last place
I want to be on my

01:07:59.820 --> 01:08:01.260
day off is a theater.

01:08:01.260 --> 01:08:02.550
So they're like, we've
got tickets.

01:08:02.550 --> 01:08:05.590
I'm like, I don't want
to go to that.

01:08:05.590 --> 01:08:07.520
I'm sure it's great.

01:08:07.520 --> 01:08:08.220
MALE SPEAKER: One more.

01:08:08.220 --> 01:08:09.290
One more, guys.

01:08:09.290 --> 01:08:11.310
ALAN SEALES: Yeah, we've
got one more question.

01:08:11.310 --> 01:08:12.180
Go ahead.

01:08:12.180 --> 01:08:15.180
AUDIENCE: So my first comment
is for Santino.

01:08:15.180 --> 01:08:17.140
I just wanted to say I'm looking
forward to the next

01:08:17.140 --> 01:08:19.040
season of "Submissions Only."

01:08:19.040 --> 01:08:20.390
SANTINO FONTANA: Oh, thanks.

01:08:20.390 --> 01:08:23.850
AUDIENCE: And my question has
to do with the promo video,

01:08:23.850 --> 01:08:26.680
and whose idea was it to
pair Sir Mix-a-Lot with

01:08:26.680 --> 01:08:28.920
"Cindrella"?

01:08:28.920 --> 01:08:29.720
SANTINO FONTANA: Oh,
that's right.

01:08:29.720 --> 01:08:31.010
That was mine.

01:08:31.010 --> 01:08:32.500
That was my idea.

01:08:32.500 --> 01:08:36.740
"Submissions Only" is a web
series that basically got

01:08:36.740 --> 01:08:38.970
started-- for the girl who
was asking about if

01:08:38.970 --> 01:08:40.200
you want to do this--

01:08:40.200 --> 01:08:42.840
a bunch of actors who weren't
working at the time.

01:08:42.840 --> 01:08:44.430
She got a camera.

01:08:44.430 --> 01:08:46.319
She wrote a script, and we just
started doing this show,

01:08:46.319 --> 01:08:51.470
which kind of has had a great
following online.

01:08:51.470 --> 01:08:53.479
And there's three seasons
now that we've shot.

01:08:53.479 --> 01:08:56.120
The third season is
about to come out.

01:08:56.120 --> 01:09:00.120
I had a lot of time in tech,
which is very slow and you're

01:09:00.120 --> 01:09:01.399
working on one scene
at a time.

01:09:01.399 --> 01:09:03.000
And they were doing lights, and
they're doing the set, and

01:09:03.000 --> 01:09:03.819
they're doing costumes.

01:09:03.819 --> 01:09:06.020
So you have a lot of time off.

01:09:06.020 --> 01:09:09.300
And one of the taglines at the
beginning of the marketing of

01:09:09.300 --> 01:09:12.350
"Cinderella" was "Glass slippers
or so back," which

01:09:12.350 --> 01:09:15.319
they were hoping would both
combine the modern sensibility

01:09:15.319 --> 01:09:18.500
that we have but also
the glass slippers.

01:09:18.500 --> 01:09:21.649
And I was thinking of "Baby Got
Back." I was like, I don't

01:09:21.649 --> 01:09:22.750
know why but glass slippers
are back.

01:09:22.750 --> 01:09:26.180
It just got in my head, and I
was like, that'll be fun.

01:09:26.180 --> 01:09:27.080
Let me play around with that.

01:09:27.080 --> 01:09:31.390
So I wrote the lyrics to it,
and it's basically the same

01:09:31.390 --> 01:09:36.300
idea, the same premise that
these people are obsessed with

01:09:36.300 --> 01:09:38.000
this one body feature.

01:09:38.000 --> 01:09:40.340
And in this play, everyone's
obsessed with these shoes,

01:09:40.340 --> 01:09:41.670
these glass shoes.

01:09:41.670 --> 01:09:45.170
So just keeping everybody's
kind of personalities and

01:09:45.170 --> 01:09:48.170
skills in mind, I just
kind of wrote this.

01:09:48.170 --> 01:09:49.990
And then I started seeing
the picture.

01:09:49.990 --> 01:09:51.430
And then Robyn Goodman,
the producer, was

01:09:51.430 --> 01:09:51.763
like, that's great.

01:09:51.763 --> 01:09:53.100
You should make a music
video out of that.

01:09:53.100 --> 01:09:54.680
And then I kind was
like, yeah.

01:09:54.680 --> 01:09:57.180
And I put together kind of a
shot list of, yeah, it could

01:09:57.180 --> 01:09:59.080
be this and this and
this and this.

01:09:59.080 --> 01:10:01.230
And there was a green screen
upstairs, and I was like, we

01:10:01.230 --> 01:10:02.880
could use a green screen.

01:10:02.880 --> 01:10:05.190
And then one thing after
another, and I brought

01:10:05.190 --> 01:10:07.570
everybody up into my dressing
room with my little mic, which

01:10:07.570 --> 01:10:10.140
I do those Excedrin
things on, and had

01:10:10.140 --> 01:10:11.320
everyone record into them.

01:10:11.320 --> 01:10:13.330
And then that was it.

01:10:13.330 --> 01:10:15.470
I had done something similar a
couple years ago with "The

01:10:15.470 --> 01:10:17.980
Importance of Being Earnest." I
did a parody of the "Jersey

01:10:17.980 --> 01:10:21.960
Shore Gone Wilde" videos which
went viral, which was great.

01:10:21.960 --> 01:10:22.650
And I love that.

01:10:22.650 --> 01:10:24.810
I mean, it's just an idea that
pops in my head and like, eh,

01:10:24.810 --> 01:10:26.230
here you go.

01:10:26.230 --> 01:10:28.350
And they were all great for
doing it, and they're all

01:10:28.350 --> 01:10:29.770
brilliant in it.

01:10:29.770 --> 01:10:33.700
It's very hard to get people on
board with something like

01:10:33.700 --> 01:10:36.980
that, because you have an idea,
but it's going to take

01:10:36.980 --> 01:10:39.250
you too long to try
and explain it.

01:10:39.250 --> 01:10:40.610
So you just have to trust.

01:10:40.610 --> 01:10:42.940
I said to Harriet in that first
shot when she's in the

01:10:42.940 --> 01:10:46.440
hallway and she's running, I was
like, all you need to know

01:10:46.440 --> 01:10:48.790
is you're regal and
you're walking.

01:10:48.790 --> 01:10:50.620
That's it, and then
she does the rest.

01:10:50.620 --> 01:10:51.900
And we did like one take,
and we're like, OK.

01:10:51.900 --> 01:10:52.900
That's it.

01:10:52.900 --> 01:10:53.790
Yup, OK.

01:10:53.790 --> 01:10:55.890
And I was editing it during
the show when I was

01:10:55.890 --> 01:10:59.355
backstage on iMovie.

01:10:59.355 --> 01:11:00.300
So yeah.

01:11:00.300 --> 01:11:01.730
ALAN SEALES: Well, I think
we're getting kicked out.

01:11:01.730 --> 01:11:04.070
We're going to lose the room,
so we have to wrap up.

01:11:04.070 --> 01:11:07.510
Gosh, guys, thank you
so much for coming.

01:11:07.510 --> 01:11:08.760
MARLA MINDELLE: Thank you.

